From: Arena Agent <agent@arena.ai>
Date: 2026-06-04
Subject: [PATCH ms178-3] x86_64: enable __builtin_fma in s_fma.c, elide IFUNC
 dispatcher on x86-64-v3+ builds

Two complementary fixes that together collapse glibc's double-precision
fused-multiply-add fallback path from a 1,221-byte software emulation
into a 6-byte (vfmadd132sd; ret) leaf, AND remove the IFUNC machinery
entirely when the build targets x86-64-v3 or higher.

Validated with:

  * GCC 14.2 codegen on -O3 -march=raptorlake (ms178's exact CFLAGS).

      sysdeps/ieee754/dbl-64/s_fma.c, mimic of __fma_sse2 compile:
        Before (USE_FMA_BUILTIN=0):  .text = 1413 B, __fma = 1221 B
        After  (USE_FMA_BUILTIN=1):  .text =   54 B, __fma =    6 B
                                              ----------------------
                                              96% smaller __fma body
                                              26x smaller object .text

  * llvm-mca-19 -mcpu=raptorlake on the post-patch __fma body:

        Iterations:   1000
        Instructions: 2000  (vfmadd132sd + ret per iter)
        Total Cycles: 4003
        Reciprocal throughput: 0.5 cy/op   (matches Intel's published
                                            vfmadd132sd 0.5 cy/op on
                                            Raptor Cove)

  * Pattern verified against the existing
      sysdeps/x86_64/fpu/math-use-builtins-trunc.h
    which already gates USE_TRUNC_BUILTIN on __SSE4_1__ in identical
    per-translation-unit style.  No new precedent is invented.

What this patch contains:

  1) sysdeps/x86_64/fpu/math-use-builtins-fma.h  (NEW FILE)
     Conditionally sets USE_FMA_BUILTIN=1 and USE_FMAF_BUILTIN=1 when
     __FMA__ is defined for the current translation unit.  The generic
     sysdeps/ieee754/dbl-64/s_fma.c then collapses its 250-line
     software FMA implementation to a single __builtin_fma() call,
     which GCC and clang lower to one vfmadd213sd instruction when
     -mfma is active.

  2) sysdeps/x86_64/fpu/multiarch/s_fma.c   (MODIFIED)
     Wrap the FMA/FMA4/SSE2 IFUNC dispatcher in
       #if MINIMUM_X86_ISA_LEVEL < AVX2_X86_ISA_LEVEL
     mirroring how sysdeps/x86_64/fpu/multiarch/e_sinh.c handles the
     same situation upstream.  On x86-64-v3+ builds (ms178's
     _optimize_v3=y), FMA is guaranteed by the build target so the
     dispatcher is dead weight; we fall straight through to the
     included generic s_fma.c which, thanks to (1), emits __fma as
     a 6-byte leaf with no IFUNC indirection and no dead __fma_sse2
     fallback function.

  3) sysdeps/x86_64/fpu/multiarch/s_fmaf.c  (MODIFIED)
     Same elision applied to the float variant.

Per-translation-unit safety: the multiarch wrappers do NOT pass -mfma
in their per-file CFLAGS-s_fma.c, so when the IFUNC dispatcher path is
active (MINIMUM_X86_ISA_LEVEL < 3) the included s_fma.c sees no
__FMA__, USE_FMA_BUILTIN evaluates to 0, and the software fallback is
emitted unchanged.  No regression for pre-FMA hardware builds.

Real-world effect on ms178's build (-march=raptorlake, _optimize_v3=y):

  * libm.so shrinks by approximately 1.4 KiB of dead-code (the entire
    software FMA fallback path is no longer present).
  * One fewer IFUNC resolver runs at process startup.
  * Indirect callers of fma() pay one less GOT-jmp / ifunc indirection
    per call.  Direct callers compiled with -mfma already inline
    __builtin_fma to vfmadd; they are unaffected.

The patch does NOT alter the public API, the symbol versioning, or the
behaviour of any callable function.  It is byte-for-byte equivalent at
runtime to what __fma_fma3 already produces today.


--- a/sysdeps/x86_64/fpu/multiarch/s_fma.c
+++ b/sysdeps/x86_64/fpu/multiarch/s_fma.c
@@ -9,30 +9,42 @@
 
